## {#pcr-concept data-menu-title="PCR concept"}

[Principal Component Regression]{.slide-title}

<hr>

So far, PCA has been applied to the **predictors only** — the response variable $Y$ plays no role.

. . .

**Principal Component Regression (PCR)** connects this structure to the response:

::: {.body-text-m .teal-text .center-text}
Replace the original $p$ predictors with $M \leq p$ principal components, then fit OLS on the projected data.
:::

. . .

The guiding assumption: **the directions in which the predictors vary the most are often also the directions most strongly associated with the response.**

. . .

This is an assumption — but a reasonable one in many real settings.

---

## {#pcr-3d-setup data-menu-title="PCR 3D example"}

[PCR: 3D example setup]{.slide-title}

<hr>

Using our 3D $x/y/z$ data, suppose we observe a response $Y$:

$$Y = 2x + 2y + 2z + \varepsilon$$

So the true coefficients are **2 for all three predictors**.

. . .

**Standard OLS** must estimate three separate coefficients:

::: {#8f2c9a33 .cell execution_count=11}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
Predictor  OLS coefficient
        x            2.039
        y            1.884
        z            2.127

OLS intercept: -0.072   |   OLS R²: 0.944
```
:::
:::


. . .

Since PC1 captures 95\.1 % of the variance in $x$, $y$, $z$, we can try replacing all three variables with just PC1.

---

