## {#checkin-compare-a data-menu-title="Check-in: comparing methods (answer)"}

[Check-in: comparing PCR, ridge, and lasso]{.slide-title}

<hr>

::: {#b65bd871 .cell execution_count=19}

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
                Method CV-MSE
OLS (all 8 predictors) 14.664
           PCR (M = 8) 14.664
  Ridge (CV-optimal λ) 14.628
  Lasso (CV-optimal λ) 14.496
```
:::
:::


::: {.body-text-s}
1. **PCR should improve on OLS** because OLS overfits when predictors include irrelevant ones. Reducing to the most informative PC directions lowers variance at a small cost in bias.

2. **Lasso** tends to perform best because it can exactly zero out the two truly irrelevant predictors (`aspect` and `canopy`), directly matching the structure of the true model.

3. **PCR cannot perform variable selection**: it retains all original predictors in each PC (with varying loadings) and cannot set any loading to exactly zero. In a truly sparse setting, lasso has a structural advantage. PCR works best when the signal is spread across many predictors that share a common underlying structure.
:::
